00:01:43.590 --> 00:01:44.440
with all of you.

00:01:44.440 --> 00:01:49.560
So to begin with, this is
a community in rural Ghana.

00:01:49.560 --> 00:01:51.920
Pencils of Promise
began in 2008.

00:01:51.920 --> 00:01:55.800
I put $25 into a bank account
in hopes of building one school,

00:01:55.800 --> 00:01:59.490
and that first school
was in rural Laos.

00:01:59.490 --> 00:02:01.800
Over time, what I
saw was that not only

00:02:01.800 --> 00:02:06.810
did I have a personal passion
for attempting and really

00:02:06.810 --> 00:02:11.340
guiding, I think, communities,
in particular communities

00:02:11.340 --> 00:02:14.190
of poverty in rural parts
of the developing world,

00:02:14.190 --> 00:02:16.590
to enable their future
generations of children

00:02:16.590 --> 00:02:18.300
to gain access to
better education.

00:02:18.300 --> 00:02:21.000
But that idea really resonated
with a lot of people,

00:02:21.000 --> 00:02:23.800
in particular, young
people across the country.

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:25.410
And so what started
in rural Laos

00:02:25.410 --> 00:02:28.500
grew to Nicaragua and
Guatemala, eventually Ghana.

00:02:28.500 --> 00:02:32.070
And this was a community that I
entered with some of our staff.

00:02:32.070 --> 00:02:34.590
And what we saw was
that about 800 people

00:02:34.590 --> 00:02:36.270
live in this community.

00:02:36.270 --> 00:02:39.210
And this was considered the
school for the entire village.

00:02:39.210 --> 00:02:41.600
So you can imagine, obviously,
these children were not

00:02:41.600 --> 00:02:43.350
getting access to the
quality of education

00:02:43.350 --> 00:02:45.000
that we would all want for them.

00:02:45.000 --> 00:02:48.540
And with the support of actually
a school in the United States--

00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:49.950
in Chicago--

00:02:49.950 --> 00:02:52.470
that put together a
peer-to-peer fundraiser,

00:02:52.470 --> 00:02:54.990
we were able to raise
the funds to go and work

00:02:54.990 --> 00:02:57.120
with this community
directly to really transform

00:02:57.120 --> 00:02:59.040
the lives of those children.

00:02:59.040 --> 00:03:01.435
And it transformed
from this into this,

00:03:01.435 --> 00:03:03.310
which is what a completed
a Pencil of Promise

00:03:03.310 --> 00:03:04.420
school looks like.

00:03:04.420 --> 00:03:07.394
And I spent a lot of time over
this last decade going, really,

00:03:07.394 --> 00:03:09.810
not only around the country,
but around the world speaking

00:03:09.810 --> 00:03:13.080
about this work, trying to
really galvanize others to get

00:03:13.080 --> 00:03:14.495
involved in this process.

00:03:14.495 --> 00:03:15.870
And fortunately,
the organization

00:03:15.870 --> 00:03:17.120
has grown by leaps and bounds.

00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:20.010
It's really found
tremendous success.

00:03:20.010 --> 00:03:22.980
And the next step
for me in 2013 is

00:03:22.980 --> 00:03:25.660
we started to approach what
felt like a very big milestone,

00:03:25.660 --> 00:03:28.020
which was completing our
100th school, which actually

00:03:28.020 --> 00:03:29.662
was in Ghana as well.

00:03:29.662 --> 00:03:31.120
I decided to write
a book about it.

00:03:31.120 --> 00:03:33.480
And that book was called
"The Promise of a Pencil."

00:03:33.480 --> 00:03:35.063
What was really
important was actually

00:03:35.063 --> 00:03:37.710
the subtitle of the book, which
is "how an ordinary person can

00:03:37.710 --> 00:03:38.918
create extraordinary change."

00:03:38.918 --> 00:03:43.560
And so as much as I felt
really inspired by the work

00:03:43.560 --> 00:03:45.957
that we were taking
on, my real goal

00:03:45.957 --> 00:03:47.790
was actually to help
other people figure out

00:03:47.790 --> 00:03:49.623
how they could pursue
their sense of purpose

00:03:49.623 --> 00:03:50.940
and their sense of passion.

00:03:50.940 --> 00:03:53.440
And so the book is framed
around 30 very short chapters.

00:03:53.440 --> 00:03:55.320
Each chapter is
titled with a mantra,

00:03:55.320 --> 00:03:57.870
and those mantras were
really the guideposts for me

00:03:57.870 --> 00:04:01.560
as I navigated the challenging
waters of figuring out

00:04:01.560 --> 00:04:04.410
how do you build a global
organization from scratch,

00:04:04.410 --> 00:04:07.060
in particular, starting
in late 2008 in New York,

00:04:07.060 --> 00:04:09.540
which was an incredibly
challenging period.

00:04:09.540 --> 00:04:12.120
And so that subtitle, "how
an ordinary person can

00:04:12.120 --> 00:04:14.910
create extraordinary change,"
is what motivated me.

00:04:14.910 --> 00:04:18.360
And I found myself on
many, many college campuses

00:04:18.360 --> 00:04:20.570
around the country.

00:04:20.570 --> 00:04:23.010
And as I would tell
this story, there

00:04:23.010 --> 00:04:25.590
were certainly a subset of
people that would actively

00:04:25.590 --> 00:04:26.550
get involved.

00:04:26.550 --> 00:04:29.190
And they'd tell their friends,
they'd tell their family,

00:04:29.190 --> 00:04:30.960
and as a result,
this organization

00:04:30.960 --> 00:04:33.210
continued to grow
in recent years.

00:04:33.210 --> 00:04:37.102
And as of today, we've
now built over 400 schools

00:04:37.102 --> 00:04:37.810
around the world.

00:04:37.810 --> 00:04:40.380
We have about 75,000
students in our programs.

00:04:40.380 --> 00:04:43.020
And what started
with just $25 has now

00:04:43.020 --> 00:04:44.730
turned into more
than $50 million

00:04:44.730 --> 00:04:48.130
raised to support these
children around the world.

00:04:48.130 --> 00:04:51.420
But as I went from
location to location

00:04:51.420 --> 00:04:55.170
to location really speaking
about the value and virtue

00:04:55.170 --> 00:04:58.746
of this work, what I found was
a common refrain on every type

00:04:58.746 --> 00:05:00.120
of college campus
that I visited,

00:05:00.120 --> 00:05:03.990
whether these were elite private
schools, community colleges

00:05:03.990 --> 00:05:06.900
in Tennessee and Arizona,
large state schools,

00:05:06.900 --> 00:05:09.042
non-elite private
schools, there was always

00:05:09.042 --> 00:05:10.500
this significant
subset of students

00:05:10.500 --> 00:05:12.420
that would come up to
me afterwards or ask

00:05:12.420 --> 00:05:13.410
a question during Q&amp;A.

00:05:13.410 --> 00:05:15.430
And they'd say, Adam,
this is really great

00:05:15.430 --> 00:05:17.096
what you're describing,
but I can't even

00:05:17.096 --> 00:05:18.900
consider the type
of work that you're

00:05:18.900 --> 00:05:21.990
describing because, one, I
have so much student debt

00:05:21.990 --> 00:05:23.490
that the number-one
thing in my life

00:05:23.490 --> 00:05:25.650
is trying to get out
of that student debt.

00:05:25.650 --> 00:05:27.840
And then, two, I
don't actually have

00:05:27.840 --> 00:05:30.120
any of the skills that
are going to help me

00:05:30.120 --> 00:05:31.500
get the jobs that I'm seeking.

00:05:31.500 --> 00:05:34.990
And I'm now hearing this as I
apply for internships and jobs.

00:05:34.990 --> 00:05:37.440
And so I started to
do a lot of research

00:05:37.440 --> 00:05:38.760
into some of these challenges.

00:05:38.760 --> 00:05:40.636
And I deeply believe in
organizational focus.

00:05:40.636 --> 00:05:42.301
And so Pencils of
Promise needed to stay

00:05:42.301 --> 00:05:44.310
true to its core mission
to support children

00:05:44.310 --> 00:05:45.610
in the developing world.

00:05:45.610 --> 00:05:47.700
But there was a huge
personal transition for me

00:05:47.700 --> 00:05:49.470
when I met my wife.

00:05:49.470 --> 00:05:53.472
And at the time, you start to
fall in love with somebody,

00:05:53.472 --> 00:05:54.930
you start planning
a life together,

00:05:54.930 --> 00:05:57.120
and one of those
important conversations

00:05:57.120 --> 00:05:59.940
is to figure out where you're
coming from financially.

00:05:59.940 --> 00:06:03.630
And what was very clear to me
from really the first month

00:06:03.630 --> 00:06:06.060
that we spent
together was that she

00:06:06.060 --> 00:06:08.526
was from a very
loving family but one

00:06:08.526 --> 00:06:09.900
without a lot of
financial means.

00:06:09.900 --> 00:06:11.316
And they came to
this country when

00:06:11.316 --> 00:06:13.770
she was nine from South Africa,
moved to the Boston area

00:06:13.770 --> 00:06:17.790
in hopes of really building a
life of success and prosperity.

00:06:17.790 --> 00:06:21.400
And if you're new to this
country, in particular

00:06:21.400 --> 00:06:24.910
or you're of the working-class
or lower-income family, what's

00:06:24.910 --> 00:06:27.340
the number-one thing that
every parent tells you

00:06:27.340 --> 00:06:29.402
you should invest and
that you should focus on

00:06:29.402 --> 00:06:31.560
to get a better life ahead?

00:06:31.560 --> 00:06:32.880
Education, right?

00:06:32.880 --> 00:06:35.400
And I think that's a dream
that we've really kind of sold

00:06:35.400 --> 00:06:37.555
to generation after generation.

00:06:37.555 --> 00:06:39.600
On my mother's side,
my grandfather actually

00:06:39.600 --> 00:06:42.540
was part of the first wave
of individuals to get access

00:06:42.540 --> 00:06:44.040
to free college in
the United States

00:06:44.040 --> 00:06:46.800
through the GI Bill,
which was passed in 1944.

00:06:46.800 --> 00:06:49.350
And it really started this
movement towards college

00:06:49.350 --> 00:06:50.580
for all.

00:06:50.580 --> 00:06:53.190
But my wife bought into
that, and she went to college

00:06:53.190 --> 00:06:55.650
initially out of state, after
two years transferred back

00:06:55.650 --> 00:06:57.540
in state to try and
reduce the cost.

00:06:57.540 --> 00:06:59.456
And after three years
needed to leave school

00:06:59.456 --> 00:07:01.830
before actually attaining that
bachelor's degree that she

00:07:01.830 --> 00:07:04.500
was pursuing, because
the challenges were

00:07:04.500 --> 00:07:06.030
so great financially.

00:07:06.030 --> 00:07:09.120
And by the time that I
met her, her student debt

00:07:09.120 --> 00:07:13.860
was at over $100,000 as a
result of these three years.

00:07:13.860 --> 00:07:15.555
And it was absolutely crushing.

00:07:15.555 --> 00:07:17.430
And eventually, as we
moved towards marriage,

00:07:17.430 --> 00:07:19.660
I said you should
really consider

00:07:19.660 --> 00:07:21.570
declaring full bankruptcy.

00:07:21.570 --> 00:07:22.742
You should hopefully--

00:07:22.742 --> 00:07:24.450
I know it's going to
destroy your credit,

00:07:24.450 --> 00:07:25.408
but I have good credit.

00:07:25.408 --> 00:07:27.110
We'll be OK as a couple.

00:07:27.110 --> 00:07:29.086
And at least you'll be
out of this cage that

00:07:29.086 --> 00:07:30.960
might keep you in poverty
throughout the rest

00:07:30.960 --> 00:07:32.200
of your life.

00:07:32.200 --> 00:07:35.619
And she said to me, Adam, that
sounds great but student debt

00:07:35.619 --> 00:07:38.160
is the only debt in the United
States that you cannot declare

00:07:38.160 --> 00:07:39.175
bankruptcy on.

00:07:39.175 --> 00:07:41.550
And I remember-- you know, I
have a financial background,

00:07:41.550 --> 00:07:43.980
started my career at Bain,
been working at hedge funds

00:07:43.980 --> 00:07:44.950
since I was like 16.

00:07:44.950 --> 00:07:46.830
I was like, that's not possible.

00:07:46.830 --> 00:07:48.320
That's just impossible.

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:49.860
Let me talk to some
financial people

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:51.940
and help you get out of this.

00:07:51.940 --> 00:07:54.750
And of course, she
was absolutely right,

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:56.410
and I was absolutely wrong.

00:07:56.410 --> 00:07:59.940
And as soon as I really
discovered that, I think that

00:07:59.940 --> 00:08:02.790
in, at least my mind, that's the
moment that MissionU was born,

00:08:02.790 --> 00:08:04.560
that if we had a
societal injustice that

00:08:04.560 --> 00:08:07.950
was this great, this profound,
and the one thing that

00:08:07.950 --> 00:08:11.340
was supposed to enable the
people who needed to kind

00:08:11.340 --> 00:08:13.860
of experience
social mobility most

00:08:13.860 --> 00:08:16.680
was going to keep them
in those places or worse,

00:08:16.680 --> 00:08:19.440
then we're creating a greater
and greater societal divide

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:21.987
between the classes,
which obviously leads us

00:08:21.987 --> 00:08:24.570
to this huge political division
and all these other challenges

00:08:24.570 --> 00:08:26.440
that we're now
facing as a country.

00:08:26.440 --> 00:08:29.010
And so I said I need
to research this more.

00:08:29.010 --> 00:08:33.450
And I'll show you a chart
that a friend of mine,

00:08:33.450 --> 00:08:35.730
Neil Blumenthal, sent
me a few months ago.

00:08:35.730 --> 00:08:37.407
Neil is the
co-founder and co-CEO

00:08:37.407 --> 00:08:39.990
of Warby Parker and someone who
is also passionate about this,

00:08:39.990 --> 00:08:41.909
because he's seeing
it on his team.

00:08:41.909 --> 00:08:45.090
Some of the challenges of
finding work-ready talent,

00:08:45.090 --> 00:08:46.410
especially out of undergrad.

00:08:46.410 --> 00:08:50.060
And so this is the price
change in consumer goods

00:08:50.060 --> 00:08:52.350
over the last 20 years or so.

00:08:52.350 --> 00:08:55.350
And what you can see is that the
bottom, things like software,

00:08:55.350 --> 00:08:57.900
toys, new cars, clothing,
et cetera, essentially

00:08:57.900 --> 00:09:00.630
luxury consumer goods, have
actually drastically come down.

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:02.947
Much more people can access
them than ever before.

00:09:02.947 --> 00:09:05.280
What you see at the very top
is that education has never

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:06.510
been more expensive.

00:09:06.510 --> 00:09:09.330
And even more expensive
than traditional education

00:09:09.330 --> 00:09:10.860
is college tuition.

00:09:10.860 --> 00:09:14.010
It's risen more than essentially
any other incurred fee

00:09:14.010 --> 00:09:16.249
that someone is going to
take on in their life.

00:09:16.249 --> 00:09:18.540
As I started to dig further
and further into this, what

00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:20.820
I realized was that
not only do you

00:09:20.820 --> 00:09:22.860
see this huge
growth, the red line

00:09:22.860 --> 00:09:25.650
in the cost of getting
an undergraduate degree,

00:09:25.650 --> 00:09:27.900
but the blue line is
the average earnings

00:09:27.900 --> 00:09:30.930
of a bachelor-degree holder
between the ages of 24 and 34.

00:09:30.930 --> 00:09:32.640
And so that's
actually gone down.

00:09:32.640 --> 00:09:35.730
And so what we have
is, one, this situation

00:09:35.730 --> 00:09:38.640
where any person who's
entering college and has

00:09:38.640 --> 00:09:41.350
to take on debt, that number is
just increasing and increasing.

00:09:41.350 --> 00:09:43.654
And now it's becoming
oftentimes insurmountable.

00:09:43.654 --> 00:09:45.570
Today's entering freshmen
will have on average

00:09:45.570 --> 00:09:50.880
$50,000 of debt by the time
they graduate, if they graduate.

00:09:50.880 --> 00:09:54.300
And only a much lower
percentage than we

00:09:54.300 --> 00:09:56.927
actually anticipate graduate.

00:09:56.927 --> 00:09:59.010
And then, two, they actually
don't have the skills

00:09:59.010 --> 00:09:59.610
that they need.

00:09:59.610 --> 00:10:01.110
About 3/4 believe
that their college

00:10:01.110 --> 00:10:04.080
has failed to prepare
them for the real world.

00:10:04.080 --> 00:10:06.840
And so there are
three macro shifts

00:10:06.840 --> 00:10:09.840
that I observed in
really 2016 into 2017,

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:11.760
and now here we
are in 2018, that

00:10:11.760 --> 00:10:13.740
would enable a very
new model for us

00:10:13.740 --> 00:10:17.730
to really kind of recreate,
reinvent, and reinvigorate

00:10:17.730 --> 00:10:21.000
this very oftentimes
averse-to-change space

00:10:21.000 --> 00:10:22.170
of higher ed.

00:10:22.170 --> 00:10:25.170
And so the first is
historically credentials

00:10:25.170 --> 00:10:27.270
were really the
metric for success.

00:10:27.270 --> 00:10:29.160
People just said, OK,
do you have a degree?

00:10:29.160 --> 00:10:30.997
Yes, then you must be
skilled, because we

00:10:30.997 --> 00:10:33.330
didn't have all this other
information on an individual.

00:10:33.330 --> 00:10:34.954
You couldn't search
for them on Google.

00:10:34.954 --> 00:10:37.080
You couldn't look up
their LinkedIn credentials

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:38.490
10 or 15 years ago.

00:10:38.490 --> 00:10:42.900
So now seeing this shift over
to competency-based hiring,

00:10:42.900 --> 00:10:44.370
in particular for
technical skills

00:10:44.370 --> 00:10:46.040
you can just put a test
in front of somebody

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:48.000
and you can assess their
technical abilities.

00:10:48.000 --> 00:10:50.580
And that's actually much
more important than perhaps

00:10:50.580 --> 00:10:52.330
whether they have
a degree or not.

00:10:52.330 --> 00:10:54.630
The second is that
historically tests were

00:10:54.630 --> 00:10:56.730
the primary method of learning.

00:10:56.730 --> 00:10:58.920
We did rote
memorization and then

00:10:58.920 --> 00:11:00.390
after that rote
memorization, then

00:11:00.390 --> 00:11:03.810
we just jumped into an exam,
and we regurgitated that,

00:11:03.810 --> 00:11:05.530
and that was a
demonstration of learning.

00:11:05.530 --> 00:11:07.890
And I think that what we are
seeing a radical shift to

00:11:07.890 --> 00:11:12.270
is project-based learning,
where it's much more replicable

00:11:12.270 --> 00:11:14.880
to put together a
group of projects

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:17.430
that a person actually
navigates through in a group.

00:11:17.430 --> 00:11:20.250
And that in itself is a
lot more demonstrative

00:11:20.250 --> 00:11:22.597
of what we actually
experience in the real world,

00:11:22.597 --> 00:11:23.430
in our work context.

00:11:23.430 --> 00:11:26.160
And then the third is that in
2012, we saw the rise of MOOCs

00:11:26.160 --> 00:11:27.574
like Coursera and Udacity.

00:11:27.574 --> 00:11:29.115
There was this huge
belief that we're

00:11:29.115 --> 00:11:30.390
going to have the best
professor in the world.

00:11:30.390 --> 00:11:32.230
He's going to get 15,000
people, and that's

00:11:32.230 --> 00:11:34.630
going to solve the
challenges of education.

00:11:34.630 --> 00:11:37.660
And what we're seeing is that
the vast majority of people

00:11:37.660 --> 00:11:39.270
don't actually
complete those courses.

00:11:39.270 --> 00:11:40.880
It's less than 5%.

00:11:40.880 --> 00:11:43.250
Most of us are not
considered autodidacts,

00:11:43.250 --> 00:11:46.150
that we can teach ourselves
and have that motivation

00:11:46.150 --> 00:11:48.670
and accountability to
complete one of those courses.

00:11:48.670 --> 00:11:52.190
And so what we are
able to do, though,

00:11:52.190 --> 00:11:56.050
is work very effectively in
online cohorts when it's live,

00:11:56.050 --> 00:11:57.700
synchronous instruction.

00:11:57.700 --> 00:12:00.570
When there is an instructor,
a world-class expert

00:12:00.570 --> 00:12:02.320
in something, with a
small group and we're

00:12:02.320 --> 00:12:05.177
held accountable to those
around us on the screen,

00:12:05.177 --> 00:12:07.510
and it's done live, that's
actually very, very powerful.

00:12:07.510 --> 00:12:10.480
And we've seen a few models
involved in that space that

00:12:10.480 --> 00:12:13.750
are able to demonstrate that.

00:12:13.750 --> 00:12:15.770
And really, this started 2016.

