00:14:46.830 --> 00:14:49.490
ADAM BRAUN: So
MissionU, in essence,

00:14:49.490 --> 00:14:52.422
is this one-year program that
focuses on real-world skills.

00:14:52.422 --> 00:14:54.380
And one of the things
that we've certainly seen

00:14:54.380 --> 00:14:56.660
is that it's not enough just
to teach hard technical skills,

00:14:56.660 --> 00:14:58.310
but people that
really thrive actually

00:14:58.310 --> 00:15:00.770
possess this whole
wealth of soft skills--

00:15:00.770 --> 00:15:04.130
effective collaboration,
critical thinking abilities,

00:15:04.130 --> 00:15:06.500
effective communication,
both in written,

00:15:06.500 --> 00:15:10.200
whether it's email or building
presentations or in person.

00:15:10.200 --> 00:15:12.260
And so we also
thought about, what

00:15:12.260 --> 00:15:17.720
is an actual viable revenue
model for a modern institution

00:15:17.720 --> 00:15:20.930
that aligns itself with the
outcomes and the aspirations

00:15:20.930 --> 00:15:22.610
of their students from day one?

00:15:22.610 --> 00:15:27.590
And so what we decided was that
before any student ever paid us

00:15:27.590 --> 00:15:29.470
a dollar of tuition,
we would have

00:15:29.470 --> 00:15:31.970
to demonstrate to them that
they had achieved success, which

00:15:31.970 --> 00:15:33.590
is really the exact
opposite of what

00:15:33.590 --> 00:15:35.180
happens on a traditional
college today, right?

00:15:35.180 --> 00:15:36.870
You take out these big
loans, you pay the school,

00:15:36.870 --> 00:15:39.350
and then you kind of hope
for the best, that you end up

00:15:39.350 --> 00:15:40.710
with a job afterwards.

00:15:40.710 --> 00:15:42.260
But their commitment
essentially ends

00:15:42.260 --> 00:15:43.926
when you walk out
their door, and that's

00:15:43.926 --> 00:15:47.210
when they usually reach out in
order to ask for a donation.

00:15:47.210 --> 00:15:49.100
How many people have
gotten that solicitation

00:15:49.100 --> 00:15:50.016
from their alma mater?

00:15:50.016 --> 00:15:51.630
Probably all of us.

00:15:51.630 --> 00:15:54.950
And so what we decided was that
when someone got in MissionU,

00:15:54.950 --> 00:15:57.200
we would charge them
absolutely no tuition upfront.

00:15:57.200 --> 00:15:58.700
And instead, we
would invest in them

00:15:58.700 --> 00:16:01.340
throughout the course of
their entire year at MissionU.

00:16:01.340 --> 00:16:04.310
And at the end of that
year, only if and when

00:16:04.310 --> 00:16:06.740
they were making at
least $50,000 or more,

00:16:06.740 --> 00:16:09.020
they would contribute
back 15% of their income

00:16:09.020 --> 00:16:09.920
for three years.

00:16:09.920 --> 00:16:12.130
And then that would be the
end of their obligation.

00:16:12.130 --> 00:16:15.350
And so it's an entirely
outcomes-based model.

00:16:15.350 --> 00:16:18.320
And we said, so when it comes
to designing curriculum,

00:16:18.320 --> 00:16:21.440
most colleges kind
of oftentimes are

00:16:21.440 --> 00:16:23.810
very separated from
the business world.

00:16:23.810 --> 00:16:25.540
We said we should
absolutely partner

00:16:25.540 --> 00:16:26.540
with the business world.

00:16:26.540 --> 00:16:27.664
This is what students want.

00:16:27.664 --> 00:16:29.900
91% of today's freshmen say
they're going to college

00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:30.967
to get a better job.

00:16:30.967 --> 00:16:33.050
And so before we ever
started recruiting students,

00:16:33.050 --> 00:16:35.570
we were speaking to
world-class companies.

00:16:35.570 --> 00:16:37.880
And they deeply advised
us on curriculum.

00:16:37.880 --> 00:16:39.650
Everything that we
teach our students

00:16:39.650 --> 00:16:41.810
goes through the lens
of employer partners

00:16:41.810 --> 00:16:43.899
evaluating, assessing,
and advising.

00:16:43.899 --> 00:16:45.440
The second is we
would create content

00:16:45.440 --> 00:16:47.994
so we have guest speakers
nonstop for our students.

00:16:47.994 --> 00:16:49.910
They oftentimes go on
site to actual companies

00:16:49.910 --> 00:16:51.630
to get that
real-world experience.

00:16:51.630 --> 00:16:54.410
So all of our employer
partners get first cut

00:16:54.410 --> 00:16:56.240
at this incredible
pipeline of talent.

00:16:56.240 --> 00:17:00.050
And as of now, these
partners include companies

00:17:00.050 --> 00:17:02.990
like Spotify, Lyft, Uber,
Warby Parker, Casper,

00:17:02.990 --> 00:17:05.000
Harry's, et cetera,
