this past year raised over
$2 million in a night.

00:23:39.050 --> 00:23:40.850
So I'm still very
involved, but not

00:23:40.850 --> 00:23:43.820
on a day-to-day, full-time
role, whereas most

00:23:43.820 --> 00:23:47.302
of my day-to-day
thinking is on MissionU.

00:23:47.302 --> 00:23:49.280
JESSE MICHELS: We
have over $1 trillion

00:23:49.280 --> 00:23:50.677
in student debt in this country.

00:23:50.677 --> 00:23:51.000
It might be--

00:23:51.000 --> 00:23:52.083
ADAM BRAUN: $1.4 trillion.

00:23:52.083 --> 00:23:55.380
JESSE MICHELS: $1.4
trillion, which is crazy.

00:23:55.380 --> 00:23:58.730
I remember reading a blog post,
maybe in 2008 or '09 by Mark

00:23:58.730 --> 00:24:02.390
Cuban, actually talking-- kind
of comparing student debt issue

00:24:02.390 --> 00:24:05.000
to the housing bubble, saying
we have an education bubble,

00:24:05.000 --> 00:24:07.460
because students literally
are taking out all this money,

00:24:07.460 --> 00:24:09.300
and they can't flip
it for a profit,

00:24:09.300 --> 00:24:11.650
just like you would flip
a home for a profit.

00:24:11.650 --> 00:24:12.680
ADAM BRAUN: Yep.

00:24:12.680 --> 00:24:16.580
JESSE MICHELS: How exactly
is MissionU solving this?

00:24:16.580 --> 00:24:18.500
ADAM BRAUN: From spending
all the time focused

00:24:18.500 --> 00:24:20.870
on international
education, one thing

00:24:20.870 --> 00:24:23.630
that I've really
seen and absorbed

00:24:23.630 --> 00:24:25.680
is that in order to
create systemic change,

00:24:25.680 --> 00:24:27.750
you need two things to happen.

00:24:27.750 --> 00:24:30.002
The first is, you
need innovation.

00:24:30.002 --> 00:24:31.460
And that innovation,
if you've read

00:24:31.460 --> 00:24:34.100
Clayton Christensen's
"Innovator's Dilemma,"

00:24:34.100 --> 00:24:35.300
it occurs on the fringes.

00:24:35.300 --> 00:24:36.140
It's not mainstream.

00:24:36.140 --> 00:24:38.300
It's kind of these outside
smaller players that

00:24:38.300 --> 00:24:40.720
start out really small,
and they're so small,

00:24:40.720 --> 00:24:42.470
and they're working
on something so unique

00:24:42.470 --> 00:24:44.330
that your large incumbents
literally don't even

00:24:44.330 --> 00:24:46.250
pay attention, even though
if they had replicated,

00:24:46.250 --> 00:24:47.570
they could have squashed them.

00:24:47.570 --> 00:24:51.215
And what oftentimes
occurs in systemic change

00:24:51.215 --> 00:24:53.040
is that as that
innovator on the fringe

00:24:53.040 --> 00:24:56.630
gets a demonstration of
success, what you actually need

00:24:56.630 --> 00:25:00.110
is widespread policy
adoption and advocacy that

00:25:00.110 --> 00:25:02.600
leads to a scaled impact.

00:25:02.600 --> 00:25:06.740
And so my goal, in particular
when it comes to MissionU,

00:25:06.740 --> 00:25:09.680
is for us to be that innovator
on the fringe that demonstrates

00:25:09.680 --> 00:25:12.200
success and then
eventually has policy

00:25:12.200 --> 00:25:14.090
adoption at the national level.

00:25:14.090 --> 00:25:16.910
And then essentially what the
US does, a lot of countries

00:25:16.910 --> 00:25:18.020
obviously follow.

00:25:18.020 --> 00:25:19.520
So a small example
would be the fact

00:25:19.520 --> 00:25:22.550
that we're using 100%
income share agreement

00:25:22.550 --> 00:25:24.500
rather than traditional tuition.

00:25:24.500 --> 00:25:27.470
The fact that we're doing that
is putting a lot of pressure

00:25:27.470 --> 00:25:29.420
on traditional
colleges to respond.

00:25:29.420 --> 00:25:31.070
And my hope is, I
don't expect to see

00:25:31.070 --> 00:25:33.560
every college be 100% IRA--

00:25:33.560 --> 00:25:35.990
Income Share Agreement--
but what I do expect to see

00:25:35.990 --> 00:25:38.330
is for colleges to
be expected to start

00:25:38.330 --> 00:25:40.310
to have some skin in
the game and eventually

00:25:40.310 --> 00:25:43.010
for policy to
actually mandate that,

00:25:43.010 --> 00:25:45.890
for students not to be required
to pay back until they reach

00:25:45.890 --> 00:25:47.473
a certain threshold,
which is actually

00:25:47.473 --> 00:25:50.840
the national policy in
countries like Australia,

00:25:50.840 --> 00:25:53.300
as well as this blended learning
model to be demonstrated

00:25:53.300 --> 00:25:54.175
as a proof one by us.

00:25:54.175 --> 00:25:56.508
There are other companies
that are doing it and doing it

00:25:56.508 --> 00:25:58.130
with great success,
and for then that

00:25:58.130 --> 00:26:00.380
to get adopted by a
lot of the mainstream

00:26:00.380 --> 00:26:02.102
incumbents as well as policy.

00:26:02.102 --> 00:26:03.560
JESSE MICHELS: Now,
you started out

00:26:03.560 --> 00:26:06.920
with Pencils of Promise kind
of focusing on accessibility

00:26:06.920 --> 00:26:10.460
and getting as many students
around the world educated

00:26:10.460 --> 00:26:13.100
as possible.

00:26:13.100 --> 00:26:15.860
Peter Thiel talks about the
current college education

00:26:15.860 --> 00:26:18.080
system, and he says it's
almost like a nightclub,

00:26:18.080 --> 00:26:22.020
like if you expand it
and allow more people in,

00:26:22.020 --> 00:26:25.482
they'll be very angry
because basically their bread

00:26:25.482 --> 00:26:26.440
and butter is prestige.

00:26:26.440 --> 00:26:26.650
ADAM BRAUN: Exclusivity.

00:26:26.650 --> 00:26:27.608
JESSE MICHELS: Exactly.

00:26:27.608 --> 00:26:28.830
Exclusivity.

00:26:28.830 --> 00:26:32.180
So how do you reconcile those
two things, kind of it's

00:26:32.180 --> 00:26:34.850
the social credential
where prestigious

00:26:34.850 --> 00:26:37.610
may be semi-important,
along with accessibility

00:26:37.610 --> 00:26:39.630
and reaching as many
people as possible?

00:26:39.630 --> 00:26:40.338
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:26:40.338 --> 00:26:43.310
So this is a big thing for us,
and it's currently a challenge

00:26:43.310 --> 00:26:46.560
that we're addressing
through scale.

00:26:46.560 --> 00:26:48.710
So we launched March 2017.

00:26:48.710 --> 00:26:49.592
We said we're open.

00:26:49.592 --> 00:26:50.300
This is MissionU.

00:26:50.300 --> 00:26:52.816
No one really had any
public exposure to it.

00:26:52.816 --> 00:26:55.190
We asked everyone that knew
about it to not talk about it

00:26:55.190 --> 00:26:56.439
until we were ready to launch.

00:26:56.439 --> 00:26:59.570
We launched March 21, 2017,
and we said this is MissionU.

00:26:59.570 --> 00:27:01.190
You can apply as of today.

00:27:01.190 --> 00:27:03.920
And we spent no money on
any form of paid marketing.

00:27:03.920 --> 00:27:06.440
And we said we just want to
see organically what happens.

00:27:06.440 --> 00:27:08.930
I did interviews and podcasts
and stuff and prospected up.

00:27:08.930 --> 00:27:11.419
But we did no
targeted marketing.

00:27:11.419 --> 00:27:13.460
So we allowed the message
to spread to the places

00:27:13.460 --> 00:27:14.793
where it might spread naturally.

00:27:14.793 --> 00:27:17.570
And we said, we have
25 spots per cohort.

00:27:17.570 --> 00:27:19.400
We'll just see how
many people apply.

00:27:19.400 --> 00:27:22.550
And we had 4,700 applicants
for the first 25 spots

00:27:22.550 --> 00:27:24.750
in about a 2 and
1/2 month period.

00:27:24.750 --> 00:27:27.340
And we said, oh, my gosh.

00:27:27.340 --> 00:27:29.510
There's some lightning
in a bottle here.

00:27:29.510 --> 00:27:34.936
And our goal is not to be the
most exclusive selective higher

00:27:34.936 --> 00:27:36.560
education program in
the country, which

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:37.851
statistically we are right now.

00:27:37.851 --> 00:27:41.750
We have essentially a
0.5% acceptance rate.

00:27:41.750 --> 00:27:44.687
We don't want to be that,
but we are at the moment.

00:27:44.687 --> 00:27:46.520
So we said, one, we
need to go out and raise

00:27:46.520 --> 00:27:49.294
more capital so we can
offer additional cohorts.

00:27:49.294 --> 00:27:50.960
We don't want to
change the cohort size.

00:27:50.960 --> 00:27:53.600
We think about 25 is the
best number for people

00:27:53.600 --> 00:27:55.460
to build those tight
relationships, to have

00:27:55.460 --> 00:27:57.770
the right ratio to instructors.

00:27:57.770 --> 00:28:00.620
But we need to have
additional times in the year

00:28:00.620 --> 00:28:02.600
when people could apply,
concurrently launch

00:28:02.600 --> 00:28:04.970
cohorts at the same
time in the same cities,

00:28:04.970 --> 00:28:07.850
expand to new cities, as
well as offer new majors.

00:28:07.850 --> 00:28:10.850
So we went out, we raised
another round of capital

00:28:10.850 --> 00:28:13.160
from some incredible
people, and then

00:28:13.160 --> 00:28:14.810
we opened up
admissions for January.

00:28:14.810 --> 00:28:16.435
We said, OK, you can
apply for January.

00:28:16.435 --> 00:28:18.650
And we had 5,500 people
apply for those spots,

00:28:18.650 --> 00:28:20.690
and now we're running
admissions for May.

00:28:20.690 --> 00:28:25.705
And so again we
acknowledge that this

00:28:25.705 --> 00:28:27.080
is a real challenge
in higher ed,

00:28:27.080 --> 00:28:29.579
and our goal is to try and scale
quickly to serve that need.

00:28:29.579 --> 00:28:31.400
But at the same time,
we want to create

00:28:31.400 --> 00:28:33.320
a truly world-class,
high-quality experience

00:28:33.320 --> 00:28:34.500
for every student.

00:28:34.500 --> 00:28:36.830
And we know that we need to
start slowly and test out

00:28:36.830 --> 00:28:37.510
this model.

00:28:37.510 --> 00:28:40.010
And once it's really tightly
refined on the curricular side,

00:28:40.010 --> 00:28:41.570
on the student
experience side, then

00:28:41.570 --> 00:28:42.892
scale really, really rapidly.

00:28:42.892 --> 00:28:45.350
I mean, our goal is to serve
tens of thousands of students,

00:28:45.350 --> 00:28:47.995
ideally be larger than any
current college in the country.

00:28:47.995 --> 00:28:50.270
JESSE MICHELS: Awesome.

00:28:50.270 --> 00:28:52.130
What does a real-world
approach mean?

00:28:52.130 --> 00:28:54.920
You guys talk about teaching
practical skills, as opposed

00:28:54.920 --> 00:28:56.450
to maybe more theoretical ones.

00:28:56.450 --> 00:28:57.830
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:28:57.830 --> 00:29:01.460
So first of all, it means having
a really tight pulse on what's

00:29:01.460 --> 00:29:03.110
happening in industry.

00:29:03.110 --> 00:29:05.586
So designing and building
curriculum in a vacuum,

00:29:05.586 --> 00:29:08.210
having to go through a three to
four-year accreditation process

00:29:08.210 --> 00:29:09.530
and then saying
you should go learn

00:29:09.530 --> 00:29:11.238
this, as all of you,
I'm sure, experience

00:29:11.238 --> 00:29:13.340
on a day-to-day basis here
at a place like Google,

00:29:13.340 --> 00:29:15.673
is going to leave you well
behind what's actually needed

00:29:15.673 --> 00:29:17.130
to solve the needs of industry.

00:29:17.130 --> 00:29:20.510
So part of it is having these
deep relationships with folks

00:29:20.510 --> 00:29:23.330
at companies to understand
what's needed to actually hit

00:29:23.330 --> 00:29:24.290
the ground running.

00:29:24.290 --> 00:29:28.430
The second is, I think,
a profound acknowledgment

00:29:28.430 --> 00:29:32.150
that you need to bring that
real world into the curricular

00:29:32.150 --> 00:29:32.960
design.

00:29:32.960 --> 00:29:35.420
And so, as I mentioned,
we have our--

00:29:35.420 --> 00:29:38.510
I went to a great college,
and I loved my experience.

00:29:38.510 --> 00:29:42.980
But I don't think more than
once did I ever get exposure

00:29:42.980 --> 00:29:45.380
to a public speaker who came
in and addressed a class

00:29:45.380 --> 00:29:48.860
that I was in that actually
was working at a company.

00:29:48.860 --> 00:29:50.000
It was so rare.

00:29:50.000 --> 00:29:52.040
And so for our
students, last week

00:29:52.040 --> 00:29:54.350
the global head of artist
marketing at Spotify

00:29:54.350 --> 00:29:56.340
spent an hour just with
a group of 30 students.

00:29:56.340 --> 00:29:57.810
And that's like
on a weekly basis,

00:29:57.810 --> 00:30:00.756
a top-tier person comes
in and addresses them.

00:30:00.756 --> 00:30:02.630
But then the second is
actually teaching them

00:30:02.630 --> 00:30:05.000
things that are going to
be applicable to getting

00:30:05.000 --> 00:30:07.740
a great job, to navigating
their personal life as well.

00:30:07.740 --> 00:30:09.470
So we teach personal finance.

00:30:09.470 --> 00:30:11.949
How many people here
got a deep introduction

00:30:11.949 --> 00:30:13.490
to personal finance,
how you actually

00:30:13.490 --> 00:30:16.550
navigate your financial
scenario once you

00:30:16.550 --> 00:30:18.950
leave the bounds of your
educational experience?

00:30:18.950 --> 00:30:20.630
Everyone's nodding
their head no.

00:30:20.630 --> 00:30:21.870
So things like that.

00:30:21.870 --> 00:30:24.560
We have a class
that we call Success

00:30:24.560 --> 00:30:26.444
By Design, which is
really about finding

00:30:26.444 --> 00:30:27.860
your internal
happiness, where you

00:30:27.860 --> 00:30:29.870
want to point your
compass in life, and why.

00:30:29.870 --> 00:30:31.510
All of those
things, I think, are

00:30:31.510 --> 00:30:33.570
applicable to a
real-world context.

00:30:33.570 --> 00:30:35.420
And then finally,
our students work

00:30:35.420 --> 00:30:37.620
on projects that are based
on real-world scenarios.

00:30:37.620 --> 00:30:40.914
So we'll get dummy data
from real companies that

00:30:40.914 --> 00:30:42.080
are facing a real challenge.

00:30:42.080 --> 00:30:44.730
Our students will work through
that, produce a final project.

00:30:44.730 --> 00:30:46.105
And then that
after they ship it,

00:30:46.105 --> 00:30:48.800
they can, one, publicly present
it as part of their portfolio,

00:30:48.800 --> 00:30:50.717
but oftentimes they
actually get to present it

00:30:50.717 --> 00:30:52.633
to somebody who's working
on that real project

00:30:52.633 --> 00:30:53.570
at that real company.

00:30:53.570 --> 00:30:55.700
And they get that
cycle of feedback.

00:30:55.700 --> 00:30:58.640
And then the final part is
just the back third of the year

00:30:58.640 --> 00:31:02.540
is actually working full time at
a great company or organization

00:31:02.540 --> 00:31:05.360
and then getting additional
curricular support from us

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:07.010
throughout that process.

00:31:07.010 --> 00:31:09.530
JESSE MICHELS: Yeah, one of the
perks we have here at Google

00:31:09.530 --> 00:31:12.580
is we get to speak to
financial advisors,

00:31:12.580 --> 00:31:15.800
and I think this was my
first job out of school,

00:31:15.800 --> 00:31:17.102
and I didn't know anything.

00:31:17.102 --> 00:31:17.810
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:31:17.810 --> 00:31:19.280
JESSE MICHELS: And I think most
people don't know anything.

00:31:19.280 --> 00:31:19.520
ADAM BRAUN: Right.

00:31:19.520 --> 00:31:21.050
JESSE MICHELS: They don't
know what a 401(k) is.

00:31:21.050 --> 00:31:21.590
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:31:21.590 --> 00:31:23.423
One of the things that
we teach our students

00:31:23.423 --> 00:31:25.130
is salary negotiation.

00:31:25.130 --> 00:31:27.710
And I remember sitting
with a reporter

00:31:27.710 --> 00:31:30.805
from a major media
company explaining that.

00:31:30.805 --> 00:31:32.930
And she was in her mid-thirties
and she said, jeez,

00:31:32.930 --> 00:31:34.669
I wish I got that.

00:31:34.669 --> 00:31:35.960
And so we think it's important.

00:31:35.960 --> 00:31:37.730
And our students
range from 18 to 39.

00:31:37.730 --> 00:31:40.810
Some of them have transferred
in from top-tier colleges.

00:31:40.810 --> 00:31:42.890
Some of them have
bachelor's degrees.

00:31:42.890 --> 00:31:45.322
Most of them have some type
of college but not BA yet

00:31:45.322 --> 00:31:46.780
and are looking
out and saying, why

00:31:46.780 --> 00:31:47.940
would I take on
this much more debt

00:31:47.940 --> 00:31:50.120
to get this piece of
paper that isn't actually

00:31:50.120 --> 00:31:52.619
going to be of greatest value,
whereas MissionU will be.

00:31:52.619 --> 00:31:55.160
JESSE MICHELS: There seems to
be a special interest right now

00:31:55.160 --> 00:31:57.180
on learning how to learn.

00:31:57.180 --> 00:31:59.900
That's actually the most popular
course on Coursera right now.

00:31:59.900 --> 00:32:02.210
Barbara Oakley teaches it.

00:32:02.210 --> 00:32:08.300
Do you guys incorporate the most
recent neuroscientific findings

00:32:08.300 --> 00:32:10.190
and findings about
just how to learn

00:32:10.190 --> 00:32:13.460
and how cognition
happens in MissionU?

00:32:13.460 --> 00:32:14.450
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:32:14.450 --> 00:32:16.680
This is the obsession
of my co-founder, Mike.

00:32:16.680 --> 00:32:18.200
So Mike's our Chief
Product Officer,

00:32:18.200 --> 00:32:20.550
and he oversees both
curriculum and technologies

00:32:20.550 --> 00:32:22.629
and work with software
engineer as well.

00:32:22.629 --> 00:32:24.670
So all this stuff that
you were seeing on Google,

00:32:24.670 --> 00:32:28.100
he's overseeing and designing
with Jen, who you heard.

00:32:28.100 --> 00:32:32.420
And yeah, if you saw the
slack channels of our team,

00:32:32.420 --> 00:32:34.670
like you would just think
these people are the biggest

00:32:34.670 --> 00:32:37.220
education nerds in the world.

00:32:37.220 --> 00:32:39.640
So yeah, we obsess and kind
of geek out over that stuff.

00:32:39.640 --> 00:32:41.950
And then we have
incredible advisors

00:32:41.950 --> 00:32:44.500
like Dr. Tony Wagner from
Harvard or Fern Mandelbaum

00:32:44.500 --> 00:32:46.190
from the lecture at Stanford.

00:32:46.190 --> 00:32:49.900
And so we're constantly kind
of digging into the latest

00:32:49.900 --> 00:32:51.340
learning science.

00:32:51.340 --> 00:32:54.576
Part of that applies into
how the actual structure

00:32:54.576 --> 00:32:55.450
of the program looks.

00:32:55.450 --> 00:32:58.730
So for example, we tell
every student that--

00:32:58.730 --> 00:33:01.119
so one thing that I'll
share is I actually call

00:33:01.119 --> 00:33:02.410
every student when they get in.

00:33:02.410 --> 00:33:03.910
So the actual
admissions acceptance

00:33:03.910 --> 00:33:06.730
is me calling them
kind of as a surprise,

00:33:06.730 --> 00:33:09.367
and they always answer and
say, hi, who's calling?

00:33:09.367 --> 00:33:10.450
And I say it's Adam Braun.

00:33:10.450 --> 00:33:12.670
I'm from MissionU, and then
they're like, oh, uh, hi.

00:33:12.670 --> 00:33:13.720
How's it going?

00:33:13.720 --> 00:33:14.775
What's up?

00:33:14.775 --> 00:33:16.150
And then I'll say
how's your day?

00:33:16.150 --> 00:33:17.691
And they say it's
good, and I'll say,

00:33:17.691 --> 00:33:19.270
OK well, hopefully
it's a lot better,

00:33:19.270 --> 00:33:20.500
because I wanted to share
with you that you got in.

00:33:20.500 --> 00:33:21.410
And they're all excited.

00:33:21.410 --> 00:33:22.680
And then I kind of
walk them through,

00:33:22.680 --> 00:33:23.620
hey, here's the next steps.

00:33:23.620 --> 00:33:24.828
Here is the orientation date.

00:33:24.828 --> 00:33:27.790
We'll send you an email and
repeat a lot of this stuff

00:33:27.790 --> 00:33:28.970
so you have it in writing.

00:33:28.970 --> 00:33:30.430
But I want to get them
comfortable with a couple

00:33:30.430 --> 00:33:31.513
of the high-level details.

00:33:31.513 --> 00:33:33.940
And one thing I share is that
you can work a part-time job

00:33:33.940 --> 00:33:35.020
while you're going
through our program,

00:33:35.020 --> 00:33:36.725
but you can't exceed
20 hours a week.

00:33:36.725 --> 00:33:38.350
And that's grounded
in learning science

00:33:38.350 --> 00:33:42.610
that shows that if you exceed
20 hours a week of a job

00:33:42.610 --> 00:33:45.500
while you're trying to focus on
a primary academic commitment,

00:33:45.500 --> 00:33:47.750
your success in that program
really falls off the map.

00:33:47.750 --> 00:33:50.390
So things like that
are applicable for us.

00:33:50.390 --> 00:33:52.460
JESSE MICHELS: And
kind of reconciling

00:33:52.460 --> 00:33:54.890
teaching practical skills
and emphasizing that

00:33:54.890 --> 00:33:58.820
with just a liberal arts
education to begin with,

00:33:58.820 --> 00:34:01.220
I can imagine where you
kind of fall on that.

00:34:01.220 --> 00:34:02.990
But there are people
like Fareed Zakaria

00:34:02.990 --> 00:34:05.369
who talk about the
loss of liberal arts

00:34:05.369 --> 00:34:06.410
education in the country.

00:34:06.410 --> 00:34:08.840
I went to Columbia,
and I'm still

00:34:08.840 --> 00:34:11.389
trying to figure out whether
reading Plato helps me

00:34:11.389 --> 00:34:12.500
every day.

00:34:12.500 --> 00:34:15.510
But yeah, where do
you stand on that?

00:34:15.510 --> 00:34:18.870
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah, my belief
on this is very firm.

00:34:18.870 --> 00:34:20.690
I think there is
tremendous value

00:34:20.690 --> 00:34:23.550
in the ideals behind a
liberal arts education.

00:34:23.550 --> 00:34:28.730
So self-discovery, critical
thinking, reasoning, morality,

00:34:28.730 --> 00:34:31.000
all of these things are
really, really essential

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:33.210
as part of a
formative education.

00:34:33.210 --> 00:34:36.170
The problem is, those things
are actually not taught

00:34:36.170 --> 00:34:39.020
in a meaningful capacity in the
vast majority of liberal arts

00:34:39.020 --> 00:34:40.130
programs in this country.

00:34:40.130 --> 00:34:42.170
What liberal arts
has kind of become

00:34:42.170 --> 00:34:44.120
is general education,
where you're just

00:34:44.120 --> 00:34:46.280
asked to read a series of
texts and suddenly you're

00:34:46.280 --> 00:34:48.620
supposed to be expected
to achieve these things.

00:34:48.620 --> 00:34:51.020
So some schools do
it well but very few.

00:34:51.020 --> 00:34:53.533
The two places that I think
that it's best achieved

00:34:53.533 --> 00:34:55.699
are through two courses
that are taught at Stanford.

00:34:55.699 --> 00:34:57.115
One is called
Designing Your Life.

00:34:57.115 --> 00:35:00.530
It's the most popular class
in undergrad at Stanford.

00:35:00.530 --> 00:35:04.250
And then the second is called
interpersonal dynamics, taught

00:35:04.250 --> 00:35:06.860
at Stanford GSP, but
known as Touchy-Feely.

00:35:06.860 --> 00:35:09.629
And if anyone here has
gone to GSP or know

00:35:09.629 --> 00:35:11.420
someone that's gone
GSP, this is the course

00:35:11.420 --> 00:35:14.040
that they will say is the most
transformative in their life.

00:35:14.040 --> 00:35:15.800
And so we actually
have former lecturers

00:35:15.800 --> 00:35:19.730
from those two courses who are
full time on staff in MissionU.

00:35:19.730 --> 00:35:21.320
And our students go
through something

00:35:21.320 --> 00:35:23.220
that is very, very similar.

00:35:23.220 --> 00:35:26.510
We call it iLabs or similar
to the T groups there.

00:35:26.510 --> 00:35:29.720
And when you mix that with
the hard technical skills,

00:35:29.720 --> 00:35:31.640
that's actually when
you create a really

00:35:31.640 --> 00:35:33.349
profound transformation
in an individual.

00:35:33.349 --> 00:35:35.223
So I think it's important
that we incorporate

00:35:35.223 --> 00:35:37.520
the ideals of a liberal
arts but that you mix it

00:35:37.520 --> 00:35:41.240
with the actual hard and soft
skills that will help somebody

00:35:41.240 --> 00:35:43.634
get a job to pay back
the debt that they've

00:35:43.634 --> 00:35:45.800
taken on, if they gone to
a traditional liberal arts

00:35:45.800 --> 00:35:46.970
school.

00:35:46.970 --> 00:35:49.190
And we really seek to
blend that at MissionU.

00:35:49.190 --> 00:35:51.200
JESSE MICHELS: So
is that really how

00:35:51.200 --> 00:35:55.107
you stay away from being
considered like a trade school?

00:35:55.107 --> 00:35:56.940
Because there are a lot
of schools out there

00:35:56.940 --> 00:35:59.710
that are like, I don't
like my career right now,

00:35:59.710 --> 00:36:01.880
and so I'll switch
and go to this school.

00:36:01.880 --> 00:36:03.561
And then it's just
kind of a pivot.

00:36:03.561 --> 00:36:04.310
ADAM BRAUN: Right.

00:36:04.310 --> 00:36:05.540
JESSE MICHELS: Is that
how you kind of stray away

00:36:05.540 --> 00:36:07.250
from that, by having
these kind of structures?

00:36:07.250 --> 00:36:08.690
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah, I
think what we've seen

00:36:08.690 --> 00:36:10.880
is there's a lot of schools
that are out there that

00:36:10.880 --> 00:36:13.760
are very effective at helping
you get into a new industry

00:36:13.760 --> 00:36:15.110
and lock in a first job.

00:36:15.110 --> 00:36:16.210
That's not our goal.

00:36:16.210 --> 00:36:18.920
Our students only
send us $1 if they're

00:36:18.920 --> 00:36:21.300
successful not only
in getting the job,

00:36:21.300 --> 00:36:23.850
but they need to be successful
for three-plus years.

00:36:23.850 --> 00:36:27.050
And so we want to prepare
them for an extraordinary life

00:36:27.050 --> 00:36:28.239
and career ahead.

00:36:28.239 --> 00:36:30.530
And part of that is learning
this hard technical skill,

00:36:30.530 --> 00:36:32.330
but actually a
much bigger part is

00:36:32.330 --> 00:36:34.760
the soft skills and that
holistic self-development.

00:36:34.760 --> 00:36:37.610
And if you spoke to any
student that's at MissionU,

00:36:37.610 --> 00:36:40.040
they'll say that
they needed one to be

00:36:40.040 --> 00:36:42.500
able to succeed in the
other, that when they really

00:36:42.500 --> 00:36:45.500
hit that kind of sticking
point in learning Python or SQL

00:36:45.500 --> 00:36:48.080
or Excel modeling, it's actually
the group discussion that

00:36:48.080 --> 00:36:49.850
will happen in iLab
that gives them

00:36:49.850 --> 00:36:52.050
the confidence and
the self-awareness

00:36:52.050 --> 00:36:54.050
to be able to progress
through those challenges.

00:36:54.050 --> 00:36:56.300
JESSE MICHELS: Do you have
kind of like a 10-year game

00:36:56.300 --> 00:36:57.200
plan for MissionU?

00:36:57.200 --> 00:36:59.360
It seems like
right now you might

00:36:59.360 --> 00:37:01.665
be going kind of
the Uber-Tesla model

00:37:01.665 --> 00:37:04.290
where you start kind of premium
and then you kind of widen out.

00:37:04.290 --> 00:37:04.998
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:37:04.998 --> 00:37:06.512
JESSE MICHELS: What's the plan?

00:37:06.512 --> 00:37:07.220
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:37:07.220 --> 00:37:10.195
So one, Pencil of Promise
is in its 10th year.

00:37:10.195 --> 00:37:12.320
And if you would have told
me at the beginning when

00:37:12.320 --> 00:37:14.507
I was trying to build
one school and riding

00:37:14.507 --> 00:37:16.340
my motorbike with the
backpack in rural Alps

00:37:16.340 --> 00:37:19.580
by myself that this year
we'd likely break ground

00:37:19.580 --> 00:37:22.590
on our 500th school, I would
have said that's insane.

00:37:22.590 --> 00:37:26.120
And so I think it's challenging
to project 10 years out.

00:37:26.120 --> 00:37:28.760
That said, the
ambition is certainly

00:37:28.760 --> 00:37:31.909
within 10 years for us to
be in dozens of cities.

00:37:31.909 --> 00:37:33.450
Again, everyone
lives within 50 miles

00:37:33.450 --> 00:37:34.991
so they can come
together frequently.

00:37:34.991 --> 00:37:38.210
But the 50-mile radius
allows for more affordability

00:37:38.210 --> 00:37:41.407
than just having to be
close to a downtown campus.

00:37:41.407 --> 00:37:42.740
So we'll be in dozens of cities.

00:37:42.740 --> 00:37:46.790
We'll be offering, I would
imagine, 10-plus majors.

00:37:46.790 --> 00:37:51.530
And I think 10 years from
now, parents and children

00:37:51.530 --> 00:37:54.080
will essentially
look at MissionU,

00:37:54.080 --> 00:37:55.970
and I assume others
will follow our lead

00:37:55.970 --> 00:37:57.890
and create similar
types of programs.

00:37:57.890 --> 00:38:00.230
And it will be a
real consideration

00:38:00.230 --> 00:38:02.632
for every student that
is considering college,

00:38:02.632 --> 00:38:04.340
whether they're fresh
out of high school,

00:38:04.340 --> 00:38:07.430
mid-career, working
adult, is do I

00:38:07.430 --> 00:38:09.200
go to one of these
traditional four

00:38:09.200 --> 00:38:11.040
to six-years that's
a little bit outdated

00:38:11.040 --> 00:38:13.310
or do I go through
something like a MissionU?

00:38:13.310 --> 00:38:15.894
And it will just be part of the
landscape of higher education.

00:38:15.894 --> 00:38:17.393
JESSE MICHELS: And
are you convinced

00:38:17.393 --> 00:38:20.090
that going forward a classroom
is the best kind of medium

00:38:20.090 --> 00:38:22.466
or setting to learn?

00:38:22.466 --> 00:38:25.190
ADAM BRAUN: I think it depends
on how you define a classroom.

00:38:25.190 --> 00:38:27.410
So a classroom does
not need to have

00:38:27.410 --> 00:38:29.900
four physical walls around it.

00:38:29.900 --> 00:38:33.440
If I showed you the
engagement of our students,

00:38:33.440 --> 00:38:36.530
it looks like a Brady
Bunch style set of screens.

00:38:36.530 --> 00:38:38.540
Our admissions process
actually replicates that

00:38:38.540 --> 00:38:41.780
through a group challenge, where
we have total strangers design

00:38:41.780 --> 00:38:45.261
actually on a Google Drive.

00:38:45.261 --> 00:38:46.760
We give them an
ambiguous challenge,

00:38:46.760 --> 00:38:49.040
and then they actually build a
presentation in Google Sheets

00:38:49.040 --> 00:38:51.360
together in 45 minutes and
present it to our staff.

00:38:51.360 --> 00:38:54.490
And we record the whole thing on
Zoom and Go and watch it back.

00:38:54.490 --> 00:38:58.440
And so I think that, to me,
is a version of a classroom.

00:38:58.440 --> 00:39:01.170
What I would say is a medium
through which individuals

00:39:01.170 --> 00:39:04.170
are able to communicate in
a live, synchronous manner

00:39:04.170 --> 00:39:07.480
with intimacy and honesty
is the best way to learn.

00:39:07.480 --> 00:39:09.870
It's certainly better
than doing it by yourself,

00:39:09.870 --> 00:39:11.940
unless you have a direct tutor.

00:39:11.940 --> 00:39:13.790
So some type of
human engagement.

00:39:13.790 --> 00:39:17.520
And that can be a classroom of
sorts, you and another person,

00:39:17.520 --> 00:39:19.920
and I don't think that large
lecture halls are the way

00:39:19.920 --> 00:39:21.130
to do it.

00:39:21.130 --> 00:39:22.980
But I do think that
there's tremendous power

00:39:22.980 --> 00:39:25.432
in these small group
cohort-based formats,

00:39:25.432 --> 00:39:27.390
in particular, behind a
screen where everything

00:39:27.390 --> 00:39:30.056
is being recorded and where
you truly feel accountable.

00:39:30.056 --> 00:39:32.430
JESSE MICHELS: I want to move
on to you briefly before we

00:39:32.430 --> 00:39:36.810
open it up to Q&amp;A. Are there
habits or philosophies that

00:39:36.810 --> 00:39:39.942
help you just perform at
a high level every day?

00:39:39.942 --> 00:39:40.650
ADAM BRAUN: Sure.

00:39:40.650 --> 00:39:41.710
This has evolved.

00:39:41.710 --> 00:39:44.730
In my 20s, it was like just
putting as much work as I can

00:39:44.730 --> 00:39:47.400
and try and respond to
everything as fast as I can

00:39:47.400 --> 00:39:49.890
and make the most of
every opportunity.

00:39:49.890 --> 00:39:51.780
And like I'll sleep
when I'm dead.

00:39:51.780 --> 00:39:53.910
That was kind of my approach.

00:39:53.910 --> 00:39:57.670
I think now in my 30s and
with a wife and two kids,

00:39:57.670 --> 00:40:00.510
I've really learned
the value of self-care.

00:40:00.510 --> 00:40:04.230
And so for example, if
I work out consistently

00:40:04.230 --> 00:40:04.990
in a given week--

00:40:04.990 --> 00:40:07.650
I mountain bike and
I play basketball--

00:40:07.650 --> 00:40:11.010
then I actually perform
much better in the office.

00:40:11.010 --> 00:40:13.200
If I'm able to meditate
for 10 to 15 minutes

00:40:13.200 --> 00:40:15.510
before the babies are up
and then my house like goes

00:40:15.510 --> 00:40:19.110
into all hell breaking
loose, then I feel much more

00:40:19.110 --> 00:40:20.820
grounded throughout the day.

00:40:20.820 --> 00:40:23.580
I use an app called Captio,
which allows me to just send

00:40:23.580 --> 00:40:24.780
quick notes to myself.

00:40:24.780 --> 00:40:26.670
And my inbox tends
to be my to-do list.

00:40:26.670 --> 00:40:30.891
And so I try and practice
Inbox Zero or some form of it.

00:40:30.891 --> 00:40:33.390
And then the other, I think,
is just treating people the way

00:40:33.390 --> 00:40:34.806
that you would
want to be treated.

00:40:34.806 --> 00:40:38.220
Are you building a culture that
really values people as people,

00:40:38.220 --> 00:40:40.950
not just as numbers
on your Excel

00:40:40.950 --> 00:40:43.650
sheet of headcount
roadmaps or your org chart?

00:40:43.650 --> 00:40:45.690
And really focus on
growing those people

00:40:45.690 --> 00:40:47.190
into the best-performing
individuals

00:40:47.190 --> 00:40:49.890
that they can and the
best people that they can

00:40:49.890 --> 00:40:52.307
leads to a really rewarding
work environment and something

00:40:52.307 --> 00:40:54.139
that you're excited to
going into every day.

00:40:54.139 --> 00:40:55.350
JESSE MICHELS: Nice.

00:40:55.350 --> 00:40:56.310
What's your why?

00:40:56.310 --> 00:40:59.930
What's the thing
that drives you?

00:40:59.930 --> 00:41:03.060
ADAM BRAUN: You know,
my why is quite simply

00:41:03.060 --> 00:41:07.410
that by every statistical
measure, I shouldn't be here.

00:41:07.410 --> 00:41:10.110
My grandparents were
meant to pass away

00:41:10.110 --> 00:41:12.000
in those concentration camps.

00:41:12.000 --> 00:41:14.080
If anyone's read my book,
on "Semester At Sea,"

00:41:14.080 --> 00:41:17.670
my cruise ship was hit by a
60-foot rogue wave 800 miles

00:41:17.670 --> 00:41:20.520
from land, and we had this
Titanicesque experience where I

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:22.770
was supposed to die that
day and somehow I didn't.

00:41:22.770 --> 00:41:27.900
And so I genuinely
feel like this life

00:41:27.900 --> 00:41:30.620
for me is one in a trillion.

00:41:30.620 --> 00:41:34.320
And so I need to do everything
that I can to honor that

00:41:34.320 --> 00:41:38.130
and both leave the
most positive mark

00:41:38.130 --> 00:41:40.260
that I can on as many
people as possible.

00:41:40.260 --> 00:41:44.220
And now as a new father, I
realize that at the same time

00:41:44.220 --> 00:41:46.254
I have to balance
that with the fact

00:41:46.254 --> 00:41:48.420
that the greatest mark that
I can leave on the world

00:41:48.420 --> 00:41:51.490
is producing great children
and being a great husband

00:41:51.490 --> 00:41:53.440
and great father and sibling.

00:41:53.440 --> 00:41:55.200
So those are the
two things for me--

00:41:55.200 --> 00:41:57.450
you know, this kind
of big scaled ambition

00:41:57.450 --> 00:41:59.279
with this very
small one that I'm

00:41:59.279 --> 00:42:01.320
most happy when I'm just
hanging out with my kids

00:42:01.320 --> 00:42:02.220
in their little room.

00:42:02.220 --> 00:42:03.980
JESSE MICHELS: Do you
have mentors or role

00:42:03.980 --> 00:42:06.480
models who've really helped you
and affected you throughout?

00:42:06.480 --> 00:42:07.188
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:42:07.188 --> 00:42:12.360
I have a bunch of mentors that
I've gathered over the years.

00:42:12.360 --> 00:42:15.090
One of them is a guy named
Ray Chambers, who is probably

00:42:15.090 --> 00:42:18.300
most responsible in the world
for eradication of malaria,

00:42:18.300 --> 00:42:21.420
became a billionaire, really
started the leveraged buyout

00:42:21.420 --> 00:42:22.290
space.

00:42:22.290 --> 00:42:25.380
And I was at lunch at one
point with a guy named

00:42:25.380 --> 00:42:27.600
Randall Lane, who is the
Editor in Chief of Forbes.

00:42:27.600 --> 00:42:29.860
And he told me that
maybe 15 or 20 years--

00:42:29.860 --> 00:42:32.730
I can't remember how long-- but
he was not the editor in chief,

00:42:32.730 --> 00:42:36.840
but he was running the Forbes
400 list as his function

00:42:36.840 --> 00:42:37.710
at the company.

00:42:37.710 --> 00:42:39.130
And Ray Chambers
was on the list,

00:42:39.130 --> 00:42:41.310
and he got a call the next
day after it came out,

00:42:41.310 --> 00:42:43.389
and this guy said how
do I get off the list?

00:42:43.389 --> 00:42:44.430
I don't want to be on it.

00:42:44.430 --> 00:42:46.260
And he said, well, you
either have to lose the money

00:42:46.260 --> 00:42:48.135
or give it away, but
we're going to report it

00:42:48.135 --> 00:42:49.170
if you're that wealthy.

00:42:49.170 --> 00:42:49.961
He said, all right.

00:42:49.961 --> 00:42:51.210
I'll be off by next year.

00:42:51.210 --> 00:42:54.060
And he committed his life
to humanitarian work.

00:42:54.060 --> 00:42:56.970
And so he's been an
incredible mentor.

00:42:56.970 --> 00:42:59.460
And then certainly
my family members--

00:42:59.460 --> 00:43:01.046
my dad, my mom, my
sister, my brother,

00:43:01.046 --> 00:43:02.670
they're the people,
as well as my wife,

00:43:02.670 --> 00:43:04.290
that I talk to most
about these decisions.

00:43:04.290 --> 00:43:05.914
JESSE MICHELS: Speaking
of your family,

00:43:05.914 --> 00:43:08.190
you have a very
high-achieving family.

00:43:08.190 --> 00:43:11.460
Adam's brother actually
manages Justin Bieber,

00:43:11.460 --> 00:43:12.540
among many other artists.

00:43:12.540 --> 00:43:12.870
ADAM BRAUN: Yeah.

00:43:12.870 --> 00:43:13.860
A lot of people.

00:43:13.860 --> 00:43:15.214
Kanye and a lot of people.

00:43:15.214 --> 00:43:16.380
JESSE MICHELS: That's right.

00:43:16.380 --> 00:43:18.840
Do you ever get competitive
with Scooter about anything?

00:43:18.840 --> 00:43:21.022
You guys couldn't have
taken more different paths.

00:43:21.022 --> 00:43:22.480
You're both very
impressive people,

00:43:22.480 --> 00:43:24.367
but do you ever get
competitive with him?

00:43:24.367 --> 00:43:26.700
ADAM BRAUN: You know, as kids
we were super competitive.

00:43:26.700 --> 00:43:29.201
I think by the time we both hit
our kind of mid to late 20s,

00:43:29.201 --> 00:43:30.825
we realized that we
were just operating

00:43:30.825 --> 00:43:31.950
in such different spaces.

00:43:31.950 --> 00:43:33.650
And the best thing
that we could do

00:43:33.650 --> 00:43:36.390
is just be unbelievably
proud of one another

00:43:36.390 --> 00:43:37.830
and try and support each other.

00:43:37.830 --> 00:43:39.996
I think if you went to a
Saturday morning basketball

00:43:39.996 --> 00:43:41.820
game where we're playing
on opposite teams,

00:43:41.820 --> 00:43:44.100
you would see us
pretty competitive.

00:43:44.100 --> 00:43:47.310
But in most things, we just try
and support one another as much

00:43:47.310 --> 00:43:47.900
as we can.

00:43:47.900 --> 00:43:49.590
JESSE MICHELS: Awesome.

