00:43:53.340 --> 00:43:56.010
go to that mic right over there.

00:43:56.010 --> 00:43:58.650
AUDIENCE: I resonated with
a lot of what you said.

00:43:58.650 --> 00:44:00.630
Thanks for speaking.

00:44:00.630 --> 00:44:02.160
I was wondering if
you wouldn't mind

00:44:02.160 --> 00:44:04.080
sharing with us
some things that you

00:44:04.080 --> 00:44:08.232
tried or thought that might work
but ended up not working out.

00:44:08.232 --> 00:44:08.940
ADAM BRAUN: Sure.

00:44:12.020 --> 00:44:14.790
At Pencils of Promise,
Nicaragua was the second country

00:44:14.790 --> 00:44:18.346
that we tried to expand into,
and I built a partnership

00:44:18.346 --> 00:44:19.470
with an organization there.

00:44:19.470 --> 00:44:21.261
They kind of showed me
the lay of the land.

00:44:21.261 --> 00:44:23.970
We sent a small team
down, and it ultimately

00:44:23.970 --> 00:44:25.870
wasn't successful
for two reasons.

00:44:25.870 --> 00:44:28.767
The first was the government
was incredibly challenging.

00:44:28.767 --> 00:44:30.600
We need to work with
supportive governments,

00:44:30.600 --> 00:44:32.327
because we build public schools.

00:44:32.327 --> 00:44:34.410
The second, though, was
we did this deep analysis,

00:44:34.410 --> 00:44:36.510
and the population
density was very low,

00:44:36.510 --> 00:44:38.642
and the cost of
materials was very high.

00:44:38.642 --> 00:44:40.350
So what we saw was it
was two to 3 X more

00:44:40.350 --> 00:44:43.380
expensive to impact the same
number of lives in that country

00:44:43.380 --> 00:44:45.720
than it was in the
other eventually

00:44:45.720 --> 00:44:48.750
three to four other countries
where we were working.

00:44:48.750 --> 00:44:50.460
And that was really
tough, right?

00:44:50.460 --> 00:44:52.380
You start in a country, you
actually make a commitment,

00:44:52.380 --> 00:44:53.796
you build 20
schools, and then you

00:44:53.796 --> 00:44:56.617
have to say we're not going to
continue to expand and build

00:44:56.617 --> 00:44:57.450
our own teams there.

00:44:57.450 --> 00:44:58.540
That was really hard.

00:44:58.540 --> 00:45:00.910
But I think it forced an
organizational discipline

00:45:00.910 --> 00:45:03.210
at Pencils of Promise for sure.

00:45:03.210 --> 00:45:07.199
With MissionU, anyone
who saw our pitch deck

00:45:07.199 --> 00:45:09.240
before there was even a
company, when it was just

00:45:09.240 --> 00:45:11.550
like a seed of an
idea, would tell you

00:45:11.550 --> 00:45:14.010
that the way it looks today
is remarkably similar.

00:45:14.010 --> 00:45:15.690
There's only been one
meaningful change,

00:45:15.690 --> 00:45:17.356
and that's that
originally we said we're

00:45:17.356 --> 00:45:18.642
going to have four quarters.

00:45:18.642 --> 00:45:20.100
And those quarters
were going to be

00:45:20.100 --> 00:45:21.827
hard skills in
the first quarter,

00:45:21.827 --> 00:45:23.910
soft skills in the second,
technical in the third,

00:45:23.910 --> 00:45:25.440
and then real world
in the fourth.

00:45:25.440 --> 00:45:27.300
And we realized right
away that you actually

00:45:27.300 --> 00:45:29.430
can't divorce hard
skills from soft skills,

00:45:29.430 --> 00:45:31.290
that they need to be
taught in conjunction.

00:45:31.290 --> 00:45:33.480
And so we moved over
to a trimester model,

00:45:33.480 --> 00:45:36.820
where that first trimester is
a deep dive on the foundation.

00:45:36.820 --> 00:45:38.730
And so a lot of it is
like that lean kind

00:45:38.730 --> 00:45:40.320
of mentality, the
test and iterate

00:45:40.320 --> 00:45:43.080
and get feedback
from your consumers.

00:45:46.025 --> 00:45:46.650
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:45:46.650 --> 00:45:47.600
Thanks so much for coming.

00:45:47.600 --> 00:45:48.974
It's a very
inspiring talk, and I

00:45:48.974 --> 00:45:53.450
think this MissionU concept
is a really strong one.

00:45:53.450 --> 00:45:56.000
So I guess my
general question is,

00:45:56.000 --> 00:45:58.130
this problem of
crushing student debt

00:45:58.130 --> 00:46:01.370
seems to be a uniquely
American problem.

00:46:01.370 --> 00:46:04.340
I was wondering if you,
during your research,

00:46:04.340 --> 00:46:06.950
you looked at other countries
and maybe could take away

00:46:06.950 --> 00:46:08.540
something like
either boring stuff

00:46:08.540 --> 00:46:11.690
that you could incorporate into
MissionU or are there any--

00:46:11.690 --> 00:46:15.230
this is sort of a private-sector
solution to education problem,

00:46:15.230 --> 00:46:18.230
and is there any role
for the US government

00:46:18.230 --> 00:46:22.190
that could lead to better
reforming the education system

00:46:22.190 --> 00:46:24.010
or solving the
problem that exists?

00:46:24.010 --> 00:46:25.130
ADAM BRAUN: Absolutely.

00:46:25.130 --> 00:46:27.590
So right now, there's
a new bill that's

00:46:27.590 --> 00:46:31.820
being formed that's probably the
most significant restructuring

00:46:31.820 --> 00:46:34.664
of higher education funding
in the last 40 years.

00:46:34.664 --> 00:46:36.080
So they're overhauling
essentially

00:46:36.080 --> 00:46:37.122
the Higher Education Act.

00:46:37.122 --> 00:46:39.205
And there's some stuff in
there that I agree with,

00:46:39.205 --> 00:46:40.700
there's some stuff that I don't.

00:46:40.700 --> 00:46:42.470
But I think directionally,
it's actually

00:46:42.470 --> 00:46:43.830
a move in the right direction.

00:46:43.830 --> 00:46:46.864
So one of the
things is the reason

00:46:46.864 --> 00:46:48.530
that we're in the
position that we're in

00:46:48.530 --> 00:46:49.488
is a series of factors.

00:46:49.488 --> 00:46:52.610
But one of the important ones
that the government has enabled

00:46:52.610 --> 00:46:54.440
is that an individual
can essentially

00:46:54.440 --> 00:46:56.510
take out an unlimited
line of credit

00:46:56.510 --> 00:46:59.210
at a very young age without
any demonstrated capacity

00:46:59.210 --> 00:47:00.650
to be able to pay that back.

00:47:00.650 --> 00:47:03.320
And we have this society
that's kind of encouraged

00:47:03.320 --> 00:47:05.240
through just societal
norms and expectations

00:47:05.240 --> 00:47:06.560
that you should do that.

00:47:06.560 --> 00:47:09.920
And so one thing that's
happened as a result

00:47:09.920 --> 00:47:12.980
is that there is no
market force that's

00:47:12.980 --> 00:47:15.920
creating downward pressure on
how much colleges can charge

00:47:15.920 --> 00:47:18.860
or any accountability to
the value of that college

00:47:18.860 --> 00:47:20.210
relative to the cost.

00:47:20.210 --> 00:47:23.990
So for example, I can think
of many not very good colleges

00:47:23.990 --> 00:47:26.990
that have terrible outcomes
that charge the same amount

00:47:26.990 --> 00:47:28.760
as a school like Harvard.

00:47:28.760 --> 00:47:31.520
And so that's like me being a
car salesman and saying to you,

00:47:31.520 --> 00:47:34.220
here's this Lamborghini
for $200,000

00:47:34.220 --> 00:47:36.262
or you can get this really
crappy old beat-up car

00:47:36.262 --> 00:47:38.136
that's actually not
going to drive very well,

00:47:38.136 --> 00:47:39.680
but that's $200,000 as well.

00:47:39.680 --> 00:47:43.020
And you should buy this one too.

00:47:43.020 --> 00:47:45.140
So I think that the
government needs to,

00:47:45.140 --> 00:47:46.949
one, hold schools
accountable to outcomes.

00:47:46.949 --> 00:47:48.740
And the best way to do
that is through skin

00:47:48.740 --> 00:47:52.380
in the game, some type of income
share based on student success.

00:47:52.380 --> 00:47:54.620
The second is to actually
realistically put

00:47:54.620 --> 00:47:56.549
a limit on how much
a student can borrow.

00:47:56.549 --> 00:47:57.965
And what I think
that will lead to

00:47:57.965 --> 00:48:00.271
is colleges bringing
their prices down.

00:48:00.271 --> 00:48:02.270
And the result of that
is that a lot of colleges

00:48:02.270 --> 00:48:03.755
are going to go out of
business, because they have

00:48:03.755 --> 00:48:05.250
unsustainable business models.

00:48:05.250 --> 00:48:07.620
And that's actually, I
think, a very good thing.

00:48:07.620 --> 00:48:10.040
We need to have market
forces in place that

00:48:10.040 --> 00:48:12.950
remove bad actors that
are putting students

00:48:12.950 --> 00:48:14.240
in positions of peril.

00:48:14.240 --> 00:48:16.100
And just because you're
a nonprofit college

00:48:16.100 --> 00:48:18.230
doesn't mean you're
actually helping people.

00:48:18.230 --> 00:48:20.355
And there's a lot that are
actually hurting people.

00:48:20.355 --> 00:48:23.180
So skin in the game,
capping total amounts

00:48:23.180 --> 00:48:26.990
that students can take
out, and then the third

00:48:26.990 --> 00:48:29.810
is transparency as to how much
it's actually going to cost.

00:48:29.810 --> 00:48:33.084
It's very hard if you're
an 18, 19, 40-year-old,

00:48:33.084 --> 00:48:35.000
and you're applying to
college to actually get

00:48:35.000 --> 00:48:36.410
the clear information
on how much

00:48:36.410 --> 00:48:37.784
it's eventually
going to cost you

00:48:37.784 --> 00:48:39.756
as well as the outcomes
data of those colleges.

00:48:39.756 --> 00:48:40.630
It's very convoluted.

00:48:40.630 --> 00:48:41.782
They hide it.

00:48:41.782 --> 00:48:43.490
And Congress needs to
really move forward

00:48:43.490 --> 00:48:46.786
with an effort to ensure greater
transparency in the space.

00:48:46.786 --> 00:48:49.876
AUDIENCE: It seems like there
would be a lot of forces that

00:48:49.876 --> 00:48:52.250
would kind of be operating
against those kind of reforms,

00:48:52.250 --> 00:48:55.410
like some of the colleges are at
risk of going out of business,

00:48:55.410 --> 00:48:55.910
it's--

00:48:55.910 --> 00:48:56.690
ADAM BRAUN: Definitely.

00:48:56.690 --> 00:48:58.106
It's challenging,
because you have

00:48:58.106 --> 00:49:00.980
one of the most entrenched
systems in our culture

00:49:00.980 --> 00:49:03.830
as well as our capital
allocation in the country.

00:49:03.830 --> 00:49:05.930
But what it's led to
is a position that's

00:49:05.930 --> 00:49:07.056
completely unsustainable.

00:49:07.056 --> 00:49:08.930
I read a report from
the Brookings Institute,

00:49:08.930 --> 00:49:14.200
which is as nonpartisan,
objective, and well researched

00:49:14.200 --> 00:49:16.880
as possible, that came out
last week that projected

00:49:16.880 --> 00:49:19.760
that 40% of today's
college students

00:49:19.760 --> 00:49:22.580
will default on
their loans by 2030.

00:49:22.580 --> 00:49:24.230
I mean, it's insane.

00:49:24.230 --> 00:49:27.584
So we need to have some type
of really meaningful change.

00:49:27.584 --> 00:49:29.750
And as an entrepreneur, I
look at problems like this

00:49:29.750 --> 00:49:33.290
and I say, if not me, then who?

00:49:33.290 --> 00:49:35.970
AUDIENCE: Thanks.

00:49:35.970 --> 00:49:36.570
AUDIENCE: Hi.

00:49:36.570 --> 00:49:39.120
Thanks for the presentation.

00:49:39.120 --> 00:49:43.080
I think the problem that
